{"key":"post-15293112","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>15293112</id>\n<content>If it has a toggle valve, it's probably a sterilizer. The difference is that if the rubber blowout plug is sealing properly, a sterilizer will pull a vacuum on cool down, while a pressure cooker will not.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Run it with the toggle valve open for a few minutes each time.&amp;nbsp; This vents all the air out of the unit and replaces it with steam.&amp;nbsp; Then, close the toggle and build pressure.&amp;nbsp; You'll have to adjust the stove setting to obtain the desired pressure.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>15293261</next>\n<prev>15292863</prev>\n<first>15292641</first>\n<last>15313537</last>\n<when>1319859681</when>\n<utime>10/29/11 06:41 AM</utime>\n</post>"}